deck: Best known for her work on 'Tales of Jerry'
description:
History

Full name was Jane Jenkins Oliver she was born July 7, 1954 in Houston, Texas and she died of cancer on August 22, 1992 at the far too young age of 38. She attended Art Spiegelman's underground cartooning class at the San Francisco Art Academy and became involved with the Newave network in 1976 while studying art at Sonoma State University.

She is perhaps best known for her work of 'Tales of Jerry' where a vampire named Jerry get's into all sorts of trouble. She drew all ten editions of Tales of Jerry and there was word that the title might be carried on after her death, but that never got off the ground.
Jane also edited several mini comic series like: Dance of Death, Pagan Comix and Vampire Vignettes, all of whom were published by Geerdes.

At the time of her death she was married to her second husband Phil Hirsch and had a son from her first marriage, Justin Jenkins Oliver.

Publishing

In an interview with Small Press Comics Explosion #6 she stated in an interview that she was infulenced by Bob Gibson, Art Spiegelman, Larry Todd, Dan O'Neill, Carravaggio, Durer, Goya, Delacroix, Gericault, Daumier, The Beatles, Jim Morrison, Bram Stoker, Anne Rice and Dark Shadows.

In the same interview she stated that she liked publishing her own work because it was all about pleasing herself and doing a better job every time she did so. She also stated that she'd still like to be doing what she did, in regards to her art, when she was 75 and she never thought she was in a rush to get her art out to the world.
name: Jane J. Oliver

name: Ian Bass

description:
Mark Gatiss is an English actor, comedian screenwriter and novelist. He's most widely known for being a member of the comedy group 'The League of Gentleman' for which he co-wrote all sketches and acted alongside Reece Shearsmith, Steve Pemberton and co-writer and actor Jeremy Dyson. He's written and acted in several TV-episodes of Doctor Who since it started again in 2005. He's also written and acted in a number of Doctor Who audio books by Big Finish Production. He wrote a novel trilogy called 'The Vesuvius Club' of which all three books are available in paper and in audio books. The audio books are masterfully read by Gatiss himself who does all the accents of all the people in the books. The first book of The Vesuvius Club was also made into a graphic novel by Ian Bass. Though there were plans to make the trilogy into a movie a dispute between Mark Gatiss and the film company that bought the rights will probably not see it getting made any time soon.

Currently (since 2010) he's heavily involved as both co-writer and co-executive producer, with his friend Steven Moffat, as well as acting in the BBC drama series 'Sherlock' with fellow actors 'Benedict Cumberbatch' (Star Trek: Into Darkness) and 'Martin Freeman' (The Hobbit). Mark plays Sherlock's brother, Mycroft Holmes. The Sherlock series has reached high acclaim and consistently higher ratings and viewers, with the last episode of season 2 watched by more than 8 million viewers in the United Kingdom.

Personal Life

Mark Gatiss was born in Sedgefield, County Durham in the United Kingdom where he grew up opposite the Edwardian psychiatric hospital where both his parents worked. His childhood passions included watching Doctor Who and watching horror movies. He attended Heighington CE Primary School and Woodham Comprehensive School in Newton Aycliffe. Gatiss is openly gay and in a civil partnership with actor Ian Hallard, they also have a Labrador called Bunsen.
